               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330103-180-person1680">
                  ROBERT 
                  GREATHEAD
               <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1680" type="surname" value="GREATHEAD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1680" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1680" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18330103-180-viclabel1026" type="occupation">grocer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330103-180-victim1679 t18330103-180-viclabel1026"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18330103-180-crimeloc1027">Seymour-street, St. Pancras</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18330103-180-crimeloc1027" type="placeName" value="Seymour-street, St. Pancras"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18330103-180-crimeloc1027" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18330103-180-off1024 t18330103-180-crimeloc1027"></join>. On the afternoon of the 13th of December, I missed from a stand in the window a show-glass, with about 3lbs. of sugar-plums in it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330103-180-person1681">
                  THOMAS 
                  GOODYEAR
               <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1681" type="surname" value="GOODYEAR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1681" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1681" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . (Police-constable E 39). I saw the prisoners together at the prosecutor's door, about half-past five o'clock in the evening on the 13th of December; Conley went up the steps, and went into the shop three times - he went two steps towards the parlour, and came back, and every time he joined Follard, and spoke to him- I then saw Follard go into the shop; he put one foot in, put his right hand on the top of the show-glass, put it under his left arm, and came out with it; when he got about ten yards off, a third person came up with a wicker-basket - Follard gave the glass to that person, who ran away with it; I got ahead of the two prisoners - another Policeman came up, and we took them; I took Follard, and as we were going to the office, he said, "Don't you go to bot<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183301030105"></xptr>tle down too tight upon me - the plums are all right; they are gone."</p>
               <p>Follard. Q. Who else saw me take them? A. No one that I know of; you stood still when you saw me cross the road - I could not take the other person, but you being the biggest, I took you.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18330103-180-person1682">
                  CHARLES 
                  MAYHEW
               <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1682" type="surname" value="MAYHEW"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1682" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1682" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable E 152). I produce a certificate (which I got from Mr. Clark's office) of the conviction of Follard, by the name of 
               <persName id="t18330103-180-person1683">
                  Peter 
                  Reynolds
               <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1683" type="surname" value="Reynolds"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1683" type="given" value="Peter"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18330103-180-person1683" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - he was sentenced to one year's imprisonment in the House of Correction; I know him to be the man.</p>
               <p>Follard's Defence. I was going home, intending to call at my mother's, and this officer said he saw me steal this thing, which is false.</p>
               <p>Conley's Defence. I was not in the shop at all.</p>
